The experimental results verify the feasible photocatalytic mechanism of the proposed NCDs/Bi3.64Mo0.36O6.55 nanocomposite system (as shown in Fig. 9
                     ). Under visible-light irradiation, the holes and electrons of Bi3.64Mo0.36O6.55 can be separated efficiently. The electrons are transmitted to the CB, leaving the holes in the VB. Normally, these photogenerated electrons and holes are quickly recombined. Importantly, after loading NCDs on the Bi3.64Mo0.36O6.55 nanospheres to form binary the nanocomposite, large numbers of the photogenerated electrons on the CB of Bi3.64Mo0.36O6.55 tended to transfer to the NCDs. Therefore, electrons on the CDs easily combined with oxygen in the solution to form •O2
                     −, and holes in the VB of Bi3.64Mo0.36O6.55 recombined with water to form •OH. Both of them are strong oxidizing agents for pollutants [47]. Consequently, the efficiency of the photocatalytic degradation of the pollutants were improved.
